asons]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite book |author1=Soar, Phil  |author2=Tyler, Martin  |lastauthoramp=yes | title=The Official Illustrated History of Arsenal | publisher=Hamlyn | year=2005 | isbn=0-600-61344-5}}\n\n{{Arsenal F.C. seasons}}\n{{1925\u201326 in English football}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arsenal F.C. season 1925-26}}\n[[Category:English football clubs 1925\u201326 season]]\n[[Category:Arsenal F.C. seasons|1925-26]]\n", "name_user": "Ageaxe", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1925%E2%80%9326_Arsenal_F.C._season"}
{"title_page": "AVE", "text_new": "{{hatnote|This article is about the Spanish high speed rail network.}}{{For|the Roman salutation|Ave}}{{Other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox rail company\n | name = AVE\n | image = Trenes.jpg\n | franchise = \n | logo = Renfe AVE.svg\n | nameforarea = station\n | abbr =\n | regions = [[Madrid Atocha railway station|Madrid Atocha]], [[Barcelona Sants railway station|Barcelona Sants]], Seville-Santa Justa, [[Zaragoza\u2013Delicias railway station|Zaragoza\u2013Delicias]]\n | secregions = [[Madrid Chamart\u00edn railway station|Madrid Chamart\u00edn]], Valencia-Joaqu\u00edn Sorolla, M\u00e1laga-Mar\u00eda Zambrano, [[Alicante railway station|Alicante Terminal]], Valladolid-Campo Grande, [[A Coru\u00f1a railway station|A Coru\u00f1a-San Crist\u00f3bal]], Santiago de Compostela, [[Ourense-Empalme railway station|Ourense]], [[C\u00f3rdoba, Spain|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n | fleet = 24 [[AVE Class 100|S-100]] <br />16 [[AVE Class 102|S-102]] <br />26 [[AVE Class 103|S-103]] <br />30 [[AVE Class 112|S-112]]\n | stations = 30\n | routekm = {{convert|3100|km|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"ADIF\" />\n | parent_company = [[Renfe]]\n | website = www.renfe.com\n | gauge          = Standard (1435 mm)\n | old_gauge       = Iberian (1668 mm)\n | el             = 25 kV AC (some sections on 3 kV DC network)\n | map = \n}}\n\n'''''Alta Velocidad Espa\u00f1ola''''' ('''''AVE'''''){{efn|Spanish pronunciation:\n:{{IPA-es|\u02c8alta \u03b2elo\u03b8i\u02c8\u00f0a\u00f0 espa\u02c8\u0272ola|}}, {{IPA-es|\u02c8a\u03b2e|}}}} is a service of [[high-speed rail]] in [[Spain]] operated by [[Renfe Operadora|Renfe]], the Spanish national railway company, at speeds of up to {{convert|310|km/h|mph|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/madrid-barcelona-at-310-kmh-with-etcs-level-2.html |title=Madrid&nbsp;\u2014 Barcelona at 310 km/h with ETCS Level 2 |date=18 October 2011 |work=Railway Gazette International |accessdate=9 November 2011 | location = London }}</ref>  {{lang|es|Alta Velocidad Espa\u00f1ola}} translates to \"Spanish High Speed\", but the initials are also a play on the word {{lang|es|ave}}, meaning \"bird\". As of August 2017, the Spanish AVE system is the longest HSR network in Europe with {{convert|3240|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.adifaltavelocidad.es/es_ES/infraestructuras/lineas_de_alta_velocidad/lineas_de_alta_velocidad.shtml|title=Adif - L\u00edneas de alta velocidad|website=www.adifaltavelocidad.es|language=es|access-date=2017-08-17}}</ref> and the second longest in the world, after China's.<ref name=\"ADIF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.adif.es/es_ES/infraestructuras/lineas_de_alta_velocidad/lineas_de_alta_velocidad.shtml|title=''Infraestructuras y Estaciones''. ''L\u00edneas de Alta Velocidad''|date=|publisher=ADIF|accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/projects-infrastructure/single-view/view/high-speed-line-opens-to-alacant.html|title=High speed line opens to Alacant|date=18 June 2013|work=Railway Gazette International}}</ref>\n\nAVE trains run on a network of high-speed rail track owned and managed by [[Adif|ADIF]] (''Administrador de Infraestructuras Ferroviarias''), where other high-speed ({{Interlanguage link|Avant (Renfe)|es|Avant (Renfe)|lt=Avant}}, [[Alvia]], [[Avlo]]) and mid-speed ([[Altaria (Renfe Operadora service)|Altaria]]) services also operate. The first line was opened in 1992, connecting the cities of [[Madrid]], [[C\u00f3rdoba, Andalusia|C\u00f3rdoba]] and [[Seville]]. Unlike the rest of the [[Iberian gauge|Iberian broad gauge]] network, the AVE uses [[standard gauge]]. This permits direct connections to outside Spain through the link to the French network at the [[Perthus tunnel]]. AVE trains are operated by RENFE, but private companies may be allowed to operate trains in the future using other brands, in accordance with [[EU Directive 91/440|European Union legislation]]. Some TGV-derived trains used to run on the broad-gauge network at slower speeds, but these were branded separately as [[Euromed (train)|Euromed]] until new rolling stock was commissioned for these services.\n\n== History ==\n{{imagestack|\n[[File:Spain High Speed Rail.svg|thumb|right|Map showing high-speed ''railway lines'' currently (January 2020) in operation.]]\n[[File:HighSpeedSpain.svg|thumb|right|Map showing ''high-speed lines'' already in operation, under construction or planned (''updated January 2020'').]]\n}}\n\n=== New rail link to Andalusia ===\n{{Main|Madrid\u2013Seville high-speed rail line|Madrid\u2013M\u00e1laga high-speed rail line}}\nTowards the end of the 1980s a new line was planned to join the Castilian [[Meseta Central|Meseta]] with [[Andalusia]] without passing through the [[Despe\u00f1aperros|Despe\u00f1aperros Natural Park]]. After considering various options it was decided that a standard-gauge line, allowing for Spain's first high-speed rail link, would be built. The project was named NAFA (''Nuevo Acceso Ferroviario a Andaluc\u00eda'', New Rail Link to Andalusia) and was meant to help revitalise the stagnant southern Spanish economy. The line was inaugurated on 14 April 1992 to coincide with [[Seville Expo '92|Expo 92]] being held in Seville. Seven days later on 21 April 1992 commercial service began with six daily services stopping at [[Madrid]], [[Seville]], [[C\u00f3rdoba, Andalusia|C\u00f3rdoba]], [[Puertollano]] and [[Ciudad Real]]. In October 1992 RENFE began the AVE Lanzadera (Shuttle) service between Madrid and Puertollano and Ciudad Real.\n\nIt has been suggested that the [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party|PSOE]] government chose the French [[Alstom]] bid over the [[Siemens]] and [[Talgo]] bids for political rather than technical reasons, rewarding the French government for its assistance in capturing [[ETA (separatist group)|ETA]] activists who took \"[[sanctuary]]\" across the border in southern France.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.diariolatorre.es/index.php?id=39&tx_ttnews%5bpointer%5d=6&tx_ttnews%5btt_news%5d=4021&tx_ttnews%5bbackPid%5d=46&cHash=e01ceacfd2 |title=Rafa S\u00e1nchez, concejal del PSOE: \"Gerardo Velasco es un mal educado\" - interview with Rafa S\u00e1nchez |date=10 August 2007 |accessdate=17 October 2008 |language=Spanish |newspaper=Diario La Torre | location = M\u00e1laga}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Los d\u00edas de Argel: cr\u00f3nica de las conversaciones ETA-Gobierno espa\u00f1ol|date=1992|author=I\u00f1aki Ega\u00f1a|publisher=Txalaparta|pages=32\u201333}}</ref> Seville's hosting of the [[Seville Expo '92|1992 World's Fair]] prompted the choice of that city for the inaugural AVE line, with its being the home town of then Spanish president [[Felipe Gonzalez]]  also  playing some role. Seville is the artistic, cultural, and financial capital of southern Spain and the [[:es:Lista de ciudades espa\u00f1olas por poblaci\u00f3n|fourth largest city in Spain]], after Madrid, [[Barcelona]] and [[Valencia]], with a population of over 700,000 and a metropolitan area of almost 1.5 million people. It is also the capital of Andalusia, Spain's most populous [[Autonomous communities of Spain|autonomous community]] (region).\n\nIn January 1993 the ''Talgo 200 Madrid\u2013M\u00e1laga'' service began, using AVE lines as far as C\u00f3rdoba and then the [[C\u00f3rdoba\u2013M\u00e1laga railway|C\u00f3rdoba\u2013M\u00e1laga]] Spanish-gauge conventional track to reach [[M\u00e1laga]]. On 23 April that year, the AVE set a new top speed of {{convert|356.8|km/h|abbr=on}} on a test run. Later in 1993 the mixed-method services ''Talgo 200 Madrid\u2013C\u00e1diz'' and ''Talgo 200 Madrid\u2013Huelva'' began.\n\nIn 1994 AVE trains on the Madrid\u2013Seville line began to run at 300&nbsp;km/h, cutting journey times by at least 40 minutes and covering the 471&nbsp;km in {{frac|2|1|2}} hours, though it is unlikely that much of a saving came from the increase in maximum speed, because only a small section of the line near Los Y\u00e9benes has the alignments for 300&nbsp;km/h operation.  The maximum permitted speed is 270&nbsp;km/h between Atocha station and Brazatortas, save for the approaches to the intermediate stations (Atocha, Ciudad Real and Puertollano). Beyond Brazatortas, the line is only authorised for 250&nbsp;km/h operation, which drops to 215&nbsp;km/h in the Sierra Morena mountains and 90&nbsp;km/h around C\u00f3rdoba station.<ref>Ferropedia. [http://ferropedia.es/wiki/LAV_Madrid_-_Sevilla#Velocidades_autorizadas. ''LAV Madrid-Sevilla''].</ref> It is more likely that time savings occurred as a result of there being fewer intermediate stops.\n\nAlthough in 1999 RENFE began a mixed-service ''Talgo 200 Madrid\u2013Algeciras'' route, this was, along with the other mixed services, transferred to ''Grandes L\u00edneas Renfe'' (RENFE's Spanish gauge long-distance brand) following changes to plans for high-speed rail in Spain.\n\nThe last segment of the [[Madrid\u2013M\u00e1laga high-speed rail line]] was completed on 24 December 2007 when the new high speed railway section between the cities of C\u00f3rdoba and M\u00e1laga was inaugurated. It is a standard gauge railway line of 155&nbsp;km in length and is designed for speeds of 300&nbsp;km/h (186&nbsp;mph). It has compatibility with neighbouring countries' railway systems as well.\n\nIn October 2015 an extension of the Madrid-Seville high-speed rail line to [[C\u00e1diz]] was completed after 14 years of works and put in service by [[Alvia]] trains for speeds up to 200&nbsp;km/h.<ref name=\"Cadiz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lavozdigital.es/cadiz-provincia/201510/01/alvia-cadiz-transporte-20151001153154-pr.html|language=Spanish |title=Fomento culmina la obra de alta velocidad entre Sevilla y C\u00e1diz|work=lavozdigital.es}}</ref> In 2019 the [[Antequera\u2013Granada high-speed rail line]] opened.\n\n=== {{anchor|AVANT}} AVANT&nbsp;\u2013 Media Distancia ===\n[[File:Renfe avant.jpg|thumb|right|Class 104 train.]]\n[[File:Serie 114 de Renfe en Valladolid-Campo Grande.jpg|thumb|right|Class 114 train.]]\n\nIn 1992, a new high-speed medium distance service (''AV Media Distancia'' operating under the AVE Lanzadera brand) began between Madrid, Ciudad Real and Puertollano, using spare class 100 trains. In November 2003 a new service began between Seville and C\u00f3rdoba using new class 104 trains,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.renfe.com/EN/viajeros/nuestros_trenes/avant114_ficha.html|title=Our Trains|website=www.renfe.com|language=en-UK|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> reducing journey times between the two cities to 40 minutes.\n\nIn 2005 the brand was renamed RENFE Avant, and all services started to use [[:es:Serie 104 de Renfe|class 104]] trains, leaving class 100 for AVE services.\n\nThe construction of a {{convert|21|km|adj=on}} stretch of high-speed line from Madrid to [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]] allowed the inauguration of a medium distance service in November 2005. The journey time between the two cities is now less than 30 minutes. The high-speed link combined with high property prices in Madrid has encouraged many Madrid commuters to settle in [[Ciudad Real]], the first stop on the Madrid\u2013Seville line. There has, however, been controversy over the construction of this line as the change to standard-gauge track meant that towns such as [[Getafe]], [[Aranjuez]] and [[Algodor]], which now have no commercial services, lost their direct services to Toledo. Furthermore, since Toledo is now connected by standard-gauge track it is impossible for other passenger or goods trains to reach it that have not come from other high-speed lines.\n\nFurther Avant services have been launched with the expansion of the AVE lines to [[Valladolid]], [[Barcelona]], M\u00e1laga and [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]]. See below for details of all Avant services.\n\nIn the Valladolid line, new [[:es:Serie 114 de Renfe|class 114]] trains are used. Both Avant class 104 and class 114 trains are [[Pendolino]] designs, without tilting capacity:\n\n- Avant class 104 trains are based in [[ETR 480]]\n\n- Avant class 114 trains are based in [[ETR 600]]\n\n=== Madrid\u2013Barcelona ===\n{{Main|Madrid\u2013Barcelona high-speed rail line}}\nThe Madrid\u2013[[Zaragoza]] \u2013[[Barcelona]] line was inaugurated on 20 February 2008, after parts of the line had operated since 2003 (Madrid\u2013Zaragoza\u2013Lleida) and 2006 (Lleida\u2013Tarragona). This line is currently one of the world's fastest long-distance trains in commercial operation,<ref>It is planned that in 2012 high-speed services will link Madrid and Barcelona with Paris-Gare de Lyon and later perhaps London St Pancras (using the Eurotunnel and the HS1 line).\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.fodors.com/news/story_2917.html\n|title=High-Speed Train To Link Madrid, Barcelona &#124; Travel News from Fodor's Travel Guides\n|publisher=www.fodors.com\n|accessdate=28 January 2009\n}}\n</ref> with non-stop trains covering the {{convert|621|km|0|abbr=on}} between the two cities in just 2 hours 30 minutes, and those calling at all stations in 3 hours 10 minutes. The line includes a spur railway that branches off at Zaragoza towards [[Huesca]] in north [[Aragon]]. The Madrid-Huesca high-speed rail line was inaugurated in 2005.\n\n=== Northern corridors ===\n{{Main|Madrid\u2013Leon high-speed rail line|Madrid\u2013Galicia high-speed rail line|Atlantic Axis high-speed rail line}}\nThe first instalment of a [[high-speed rail]] corridor in the north and north-west of Spain was the 179.6&nbsp;km section Madrid\u2013[[Segovia]]\u2013[[Valladolid]] which was put in operation on 22 December 2007. It includes a tunnel of {{convert|28|km}} at [[Guadarrama]], which is the [[List of longest tunnels|fourth longest train tunnel]] in Europe. The extension of the line with the 162.7&nbsp;km section [[Valladolid]]\u2013[[Venta de Ba\u00f1os]]\u2013[[Le\u00f3n, Spain|Leon]] was inaugurated on 29 September 2015. Valladolid will become the hub for all AVE lines connecting the north and north-west of Spain with the rest of the country. On April 24, 2010, it was announced a 55&nbsp;km high-speed spur would leave the Madrid\u2013Valladolid route at Segovia and continue to [[\u00c1vila, Spain|\u00c1vila]]. Initial plans were expected to be complete by the end of 2010 but as of 2015 this line remains unfinished.<ref name=\"railwaygazette1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/10/boring-begins-beneath-madrid.html|title=Boring begins beneath Madrid|author=DVV Media UK|work=Railway Gazette}}</ref>\n\nIn the north-west of Spain the [[Madrid\u2013Galicia high-speed rail line]] is scheduled to be completed in 2019 when the [[Olmedo, Valladolid|Olmedo]]\u2013[[Zamora, Spain|Zamora]]\u2013[[Santiago de Compostela]] part will be connected to the [[Madrid\u2013Leon high-speed rail line|Madrid\u2013Leon line]] at Olmedo south of [[Valladolid]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.laopiniondezamora.es/zamora/2015/08/23/ave-pruebas-olmedo-zamora-comenzaran/866397.html|title=Los AVE de pruebas entre Olmedo y Zamora comenzar\u00e1n a circular a finales de septiembre|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|work=La Opini\u00f3n de Zamora |date=23 August 2015|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref> The 87.1&nbsp;km northern section between [[Ourense]] and [[Santiago de Compostela]] was inaugurated in December 2011<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/infrastructure/single-view/view/ourense-a-coruna-broad-gauge-high-speed-line-opens.html|title=Ourense - A Coru\u00f1a broad gauge high speed line opens|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=23 December 2011|work=Railway Gazette International|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref> and the 107&nbsp;km southern section, between Olmedo (130&nbsp;km north of Madrid on the Madrid\u2013Leon line) and Zamora entered revenue service on 17 December 2015 by [[Alvia]] trains.<ref name=\"Olmedo-Zamora\">{{cite web |url=http://noticias.lainformacion.com/economia-negocios-y-finanzas/ferrocarril/el-ave-madrid-zamora-se-estrena-este-jueves-sin-actos-inaugurales_k9AFW5D0qgcnORLXnWSYN2/|title=El AVE Madrid-Zamora se estrena este jueves sin actos inaugurales |date=15 December 2015 |work=noticias.lainformacion.com |author=Fran Hurtado |accessdate=23 December 2015 }}</ref> This line will be connected in the region of [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] with the 156&nbsp;km [[Atlantic Axis high-speed rail line]] that connects the cities of [[Vigo]] and [[A Coru\u00f1a]] via Santiago de Compostela. The Atlantic Axis was inaugurated in April 2015 and the section A Coru\u00f1a\u2013Santiago de Compostela opened in 2009 and was electrified in 2011.<ref name=\"Galicia\">{{cite news |author=Fernando Puente|title= Spain inaugurates Galicia high-speed line |url=http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/high-speed/spain-inaugurates-galicia-high-speed-line.html |newspaper=[[International Railway Journal]] |location= |publisher= |date=20 April 2015 |accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Eastern corridors ===\n{{Main|Madrid\u2013Levante high-speed rail network}}\n\nThe Madrid\u2013Levante network connects Madrid with the Mediterranean coast of the [[Levante, Spain|Levante Region]] (Eastern Spain). The Madrid\u2013[[Cuenca, Spain|Cuenca]]\u2013[[Valencia, Spain|Valencia]] line  was officially finished on Friday, 10 Dec 2010,<ref name=\"europapress2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.europapress.es/economia/transportes-00343/noticia-economia-ave-diplomaticos-periodistas-extranjeros-conocen-ave-valencia-viaje-simulacion-20101210163556.html|title=Diplom\u00e1ticos y periodistas extranjeros conocen el AVE a Valencia en un viaje de simulaci\u00f3n|author=Europa Press|date=10 December 2010|work=europapress.es}}</ref> with commercial trips starting on Saturday 18 Dec 2010. Non-stop trains between Madrid and Valencia cover the {{convert|391|km|0|abbr=on}} in 1 hour 38 minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.typicallyspanish.com/news/publish/article_28366.shtml |title=King Juan Carlos and Queen Sof\u00eda open the AVE high speed train line between Madrid and Valencia |date=19 December 2010 |accessdate=19 December 2010 |newspaper=Typically Spanish |location=Malaga |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223110939/http://www.typicallyspanish.com/news/publish/article_28366.shtml |archive-date=2010-12-23 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref> The Madrid\u2013[[Albacete]]\u2013[[Alicante]] line was inaugurated on 17 June 2013. Trains cover the distance between Madrid and Alicante in 2 hour 12 minutes. On 22 January 2018 the extension section of the line to [[Castell\u00f3n de la Plana|Castell\u00f3n]] was inaugurated introducing a new AVE service Madrid-Castell\u00f3n which cut the journey time between the two cities by further 30 minutes to total 2 hours and 25 minutes.<ref name=\"Independiente\">{{cite web|url=https://www.elindependiente.com/economia/2018/01/22/una-averia-para-el-ave-madrid-castellon-en-sagunto-en-su-estreno-con-rajoy-a-bordo/|title=Una aver\u00eda para en Sagunto el AVE Madrid-Castell\u00f3n en su estreno con Rajoy a bordo|author=Pablo Garc\u00eda |date=22 January 2018|work=El Independiente}}</ref><ref name=\"elmundo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/comunidad-valenciana/castellon/2018/01/17/5a5f4611468aeb3b418b46b6.html|title=Rajoy inaugurar\u00e1 el lunes el AVE Castell\u00f3n-Madrid que empezar\u00e1 a circular el martes con 4 trenes diarios|author=JANDRO ROURES |date=17 January 2018|work=elmundo.es}}</ref> The AVE service from Madrid to Murcia is expected to be operational by 2020, and work is being prepared to extend the line to Cartagena. When fully operational the Madrid\u2013Levante network will total 955&nbsp;km of high-speed rail connecting Madrid, Cuenca, Albacete, Valencia, Alicante, [[Elche]], Castell\u00f3n, [[Murcia]] and [[Cartagena, Spain|Cartagena]].<ref name=\"levante\">{{cite web |url=http://www.adifaltavelocidad.es/es_ES/infraestructuras/lineas_de_alta_velocidad/levante/levante.shtml |title=L\u00edneas de alta velocidad, L\u00ednea Madrid - Castilla La Mancha - Comunidad Valenciana - Regi\u00f3n de Murcia |author= |date= |work= |publisher=ADIF |accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adif.es/en_US/infraestructuras/lineas_de_alta_velocidad/levante/levante.shtml|title=High speed lines Madrid&nbsp;\u2014 Castilla La Mancha&nbsp;\u2014 Valencian Community&nbsp;\u2014 Region of Murcia line|author=|date=|work=|publisher=ADIF|accessdate=24 September 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923055853/http://www.adif.es/en_US/infraestructuras/lineas_de_alta_velocidad/levante/levante.shtml|archivedate=2010-09-23|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref>\n\n=== International connection with France ===\n[[File:Barcelona - Perpignan.PNG|thumb|Map showing the evolution of the high-speed rail interconnection between Spain and France]]\n[[File:Networks of Major High Speed Rail Operators in Europe.gif|thumb|Networks of Major High Speed Rail Operators in Europe]]\n{{Main|Perpignan\u2013Barcelona high-speed rail line}}\n{{see also|High-speed rail in Europe}}\n\nA milestone for the AVE network was reached in December 2013 when it was connected to the rest of Europe via France.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=High speed services between France and Spain launched |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/high-speed/single-view/view/high-speed-launched-between-france-and-spain.html |newspaper=[[Railway Gazette]] |location= |publisher= |date=2013-12-17 |accessdate=2014-04-11 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Paris-Barcelona TGVs set for December 15 launch |url=http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/europe/paris-barcelona-tgvs-set-for-december-15-launch.html |newspaper=[[International Railway Journal]] |location= |publisher= |date=2013-11-28 |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref> The connecting link was the construction of the {{convert|131|km|mi|1|adj=on}} Barcelona\u2013Figueres section of the [[Perpignan\u2013Barcelona high-speed rail line|Perpignan\u2013Barcelona high-speed line]], an extension of the [[Madrid\u2013Barcelona high-speed rail line|Madrid\u2013Barcelona line]], completed in January 2013 at a cost of \u20ac3.7 billion.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Spain completes Iberia's high-speed link to Europe |url=http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/europe/spain-opens-iberias-high-speed-rail-link-to-europe.html |newspaper=International Railway Journal |location= |publisher= |date=2013-01-08 |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=High speed line opens between Barcelona and Figueres |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/passenger/single-view/view/high-speed-line-opens-between-barcelona-and-figueres.html |newspaper=Railway Gazette |location= |publisher= |date=2013-01-08 |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Barcelona-Figueres HS line to open January 7 |url=http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/high-speed/barcelona-figueres-high-speed-rail-line-to-open-on-january-7.html |newspaper=International Railway Journal |location= |publisher= |date=2012-12-12 |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref> The international {{convert|44.5|km|mi|1|adj=on}} Perpignan\u2013Figueres section of the line opened in December 2010 and includes the new {{convert|8.3|km|mi|1|adj=on}} [[Perthus Tunnel]] under the [[Pyrenees]].<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Perpignan\u2013Figueres link inaugurated |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/infrastructure/single-view/view/perpignan-figueres-link-inaugurated.html |newspaper=Railway Gazette |location= |publisher= |date=2011-01-27 |accessdate=2014-04-11}}</ref>\n\n=== Incidents and accidents ===\n* [[Santiago de Compostela derailment]]\n* [[Euromed (train)#2002 accident|Euromed 2002 accident]]\n\n== Operational services ==\nCurrently the Spanish high-speed network is made up of the following services:\n* international:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.renfe.com/EN/viajeros/larga_distancia/productos/AVEFrancia/index.html |title=High-Speed Spain \u2013 France |accessdate=25 October 2019 |publisher=Renfe}}</ref>\n** Barcelona\u2013Lyon via Girona, Figueres, Perpignan, Narbonne, B\u00e9ziers, Montpellier, N\u00eemes, and Valence.\n** Barcelona\u2013Paris via Girona, Figueres, Perpignan, Narbonne, B\u00e9ziers, Agde, S\u00e8te, Montpellier, N\u00eemes, and Valence.\n** Barcelona\u2013Toulouse via Girona, Figueres, Perpignan, and Carcassonne.\n** Madrid\u2013Barcelona\u2013Marseille via Zaragoza, Tarragona, Barcelona, Girona, Figueres, Perpignan, Narbonne, B\u00e9ziers, Montpellier, N\u00eemes, Avignon, and Aix-en-Provence\n* {{lang|es|AVE}}:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.renfe.com/EN/viajeros/larga_distancia/productos/index.html |title=AVE |accessdate=25 October 2019 |publisher=Renfe}}</ref>\n** Barcelona\u2013Granada via Tarragona, Lleida, Zaragoza, C\u00f3rdoba, Puente Genil-Herrera and Antequera.\n** Barcelona\u2013Seville via Tarragona, Lleida, Zaragoza, Ciudad Real, Puertollano, and C\u00f3rdoba.\n** Madrid\u2013Alicante via Cuenca, Albacete, and Villena.\n** Madrid\u2013Barcelona via Zaragoza, Lleida, and Tarragona.\n** Madrid\u2013Castell\u00f3n via Cuenca and Valencia.\n** Madrid\u2013Granada via Ciudad Real, Puertollano, C\u00f3rdoba, Puente Genil-Herrera, Antequera and Loja.\n** Madrid\u2013Huesca via Guadalajara, Calatayud, Zaragoza, and Tardienta.\n** Madrid\u2013Le\u00f3n via Valladolid and Palencia.\n** Madrid\u2013M\u00e1laga via C\u00f3rdoba, Puente Genil-Herrera, and Antequera.\n** Madrid\u2013Seville via Ciudad Real, Puertollano, and C\u00f3rdoba.\n** Madrid\u2013Valencia via Cuenca and Requena-Utiel.\n** M\u00e1laga\u2013Barcelona via Antequera, Puente Genil-Herrera, C\u00f3rdoba, Zaragoza, and Tarragona.\n** Valencia\u2013Seville via Cuenca, Ciudad Real, Puertollano, and C\u00f3rdoba.\n* {{lang|es|AVANT}} (mid distance):<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.renfe.com/EN/viajeros/mediadistancia/descuentos_y_abonos/avant/index.html |title=AVANT |accessdate=25 October 2019 |publisher=Renfe}}</ref>\n** A Coru\u00f1a\u2013Santiago de Compostela\u2013Ourense.\n** Barcelona\u2212Girona\u2212Figueres.\n** Barcelona\u2013Tarragona\u2013Lleida.\n** Barcelona\u2013Tortosa via Camp de Tarragona, Cambrils and L'Hospitalet de l'Infant.\n** Calatayud\u2013Zaragoza.\n** Madrid\u2013Ciudad Real\u2013Puertollano.\n** Madrid\u2013Segovia\u2013Valladolid.\n** Madrid\u2013Toledo.\n** M\u00e1laga\u2013C\u00f3rdoba\u2013Seville via Antequera and Puente Genil-Herrera.\n** Ourense\u2013Santiago de Compostela\u2013A Coru\u00f1a.\n** Valencia\u2013Requena Utiel.\n* {{lang|es|ALVIA}} (mixed high-speed/conventional):<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.renfe.com/EN/viajeros/larga_distancia/productos/alvia.html |title=Alvia |accessdate=1 February 2018 |publisher=Renfe}}</ref>\n** Alicante\u2013Ferrol, via Madrid, Zamora, Santiago de Compostela and A Coru\u00f1a.\n** Alicante\u2013Gij\u00f3n, via Madrid, Valladolid, Le\u00f3n and Oviedo.\n** Alicante\u2013Santander, via Madrid, Segovia, Valladolid and Palencia.\n** Barcelona\u2013A Coru\u00f1a, via Zaragoza, Pamplona, Vitoria-Gasteiz, Burgos, Le\u00f3n, Ponferrada and Santiago de Compostela.\n** Barcelona\u2013Bilbao, via Zaragoza and Logro\u00f1o.\n** Barcelona\u2013Le\u00f3n, via Zaragoza, Pamplona, Vitoria-Gasteiz and Burgos.\n** Barcelona\u2013Gij\u00f3n, via Zaragoza, Pamplona, Vitoria-Gasteiz, Burgos and Le\u00f3n.\n** Barcelona\u2013Irun, via Zaragoza, Pamplona and San Sebasti\u00e1n.\n** Barcelona\u2013Vigo, via Zaragoza, Pamplona, Vitoria-Gasteiz, Burgos, Le\u00f3n and Ourense, with connection services to Gij\u00f3n in Le\u00f3n and to A Coru\u00f1a in Monforte de Lemos.\n** Gij\u00f3n\u2013Castell\u00f3n, via Le\u00f3n, Valladolid, Madrid and Valencia.\n** Gij\u00f3n\u2013Oropesa del Mar, via Le\u00f3n, Valladolid, Madrid, Valencia and Castell\u00f3n.\n** Madrid\u2013Bilbao, via Valladolid and Burgos.\n** Madrid\u2013C\u00e1diz, via Ciudad Real, C\u00f3rdoba and Sevilla.\n** Madrid\u2013Ferrol, via Zamora, Ourense, Santiago de Compostela and A Coru\u00f1a.\n** Madrid\u2013Gij\u00f3n, via Valladolid and Le\u00f3n.\n** Madrid\u2013Huelva, via Cordoba.\n** Madrid\u2013Irun, via Valladolid, Burgos, Vitoria-Gasteiz and San Sebasti\u00e1n.\n** Madrid\u2013Logro\u00f1o, via Calatayud.\n** Madrid\u2013Lugo, via Segovia, Zamora and Ourense.\n** Madrid\u2013Pamplona, via Calatayud.\n** Madrid\u2013Ponferrada, via Valladolid and Le\u00f3n.\n** Madrid\u2013Pontevedra, via Segovia, Medina del Campo, Zamora and Ourense.\n** Madrid\u2013Salamanca, via Olmedo and Medina del Campo.\n** Madrid\u2013Santander, via Valladolid, Palencia and Torrelavega.\n** Madrid\u2013Santiago de Compostela, via Zamora and Ourense.\nThe central hub of the AVE system is Madrid's [[Madrid Atocha railway station|Puerta de Atocha]], except for the Madrid\u2013Le\u00f3n line, which terminates at [[Madrid Chamart\u00edn railway station|Chamart\u00edn station]].\n\n== Trains ==\nCurrently, there are several series of high-speed trains that run the AVE service:\n*'''[[AVE Class 100|S/100]]''', manufactured by [[Alstom]]\n*'''[[AVE Class 102|S/102]]''', manufactured by [[Talgo]] and [[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier]]\n*'''[[AVE Class 103|S/103]]''', manufactured by Siemens, marketed globally under the brand [[Siemens Velaro]]\n*'''[[AVE Class 112|S/112]]''', manufactured by Talgo and Bombardier\nThere are also other series of trains that are considered high-speed, but do not run under the AVE name.  They run under the brand [[Alvia]] and [[AVE#AVANT|Avant]], and are [[variable gauge]] trains.  They can run on high-speed lines at a maximum of {{convert|250|km/h|0|abbr=on}}, and can also change between standard- and Iberian-gauge lines without stopping.  The trains that are operated under the Alvia and Avant brand are:\n*'''[[:es:Serie 104 de Renfe|Avant S-104]]''', manufactured by Alstom and [[Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles|CAF]]\n*'''[[:es:Serie 114 de Renfe|Avant S-114]]''', manufactured by Alstom and [[Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles|CAF]]\n*'''[[S/120|Alvia S-120]]''', manufactured by [[Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles|CAF]] and Alstom\n*'''[[S/130|Alvia S-130]]''', manufactured by Talgo and Bombardier\n*'''[[RENFE Class 730|Alvia S-730]]''', manufactured by Talgo and Bombardier\n*'''[[S/120|Alvia S-121]]''' ('''[[S/120]]'''), manufactured by [[Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles|CAF]] and Alstom\n\n<gallery>\nFile:AVE in spain.jpg|A [[Talgo|Talgo 350]] train at [[Atocha railway station|Madrid Atocha station]].\nFile:Talgo 350.jpg|AVE train Talgo 350\nFile:AVE a Lleida.jpg|[[Talgo|Talgo 350]] train at Lleida Pirineus station\nFile:Renfe clase 100.JPG|AVE \"Alstom\" trainset at C\u00f3rdoba.\nFile:RENFE AVE Velaro 2013.jpg|A RENFE AVE S/103 (Siemens Velaro E) at Figueres Vilafant railway station in 2013.\n</gallery>\n\n== Lines in operation ==\nCurrently there are five corridors with ten main lines in operation, and two spur lines connecting the cities of [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]] with the Madrid\u2013Seville main line and [[Huesca]] with the Madrid\u2013Barcelona main line.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Line !! Connected cities/stations !! Year of inauguration !! Operational top speed !! Type of trains\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''North-western corridor'''\n|-\n| rowspan=2| [[Madrid\u2013Galicia high-speed rail line|HSR Madrid \u2013 Galicia]] || [[Ourense-Empalme railway station|Ourense]] \u00b7 [[Santiago de Compostela railway station|Santiago de Compostela]] || 2011 || rowspan=2|{{convert|250|km/h|0|abbr=on|disp=or}} || rowspan=2| [[RENFE Class 120 / 121|S-121]], S-730\n|-\n| [[Madrid Chamart\u00edn railway station|Madrid Chamart\u00edn]] \u00b7 [[Segovia-Guiomar railway station|Segovia]] \u00b7 [[Olmedo, Spain|Olmedo]]