ar power]]\n[[Category:People from Pretoria]]\n[[Category:People in the space industry]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:People with acquired Canadian citizenship]]\n[[Category:Pioneers of rail transport]]\n[[Category:Queen's University alumni]]\n[[Category:Royal Aeronautical Society Gold Medal winners]]\n[[Category:South African billionaires]]\n[[Category:South African business executives]]\n[[Category:South African chief executives]]\n[[Category:South African company founders]]\n[[Category:South African computer programmers]]\n[[Category:South African corporate directors]]\n[[Category:South African emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:South African engineers]]\n[[Category:South African inventors]]\n[[Category:South African investors]]\n[[Category:South African people of British descent]]\n[[Category:South African people of German descent]]\n[[Category:South African philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Space advocates]]\n[[Category:SpaceX people]]\n[[Category:Stanford University people]]\n[[Category:Sustainable transport pioneers]]\n[[Category:Tesla, Inc. people]]\n[[Category:The Boring Company]]\n[[Category:Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:Science fiction fans]]\n", "name_user": "Ericahls", "label": "safe", "comment": "added by Elon's request. Business Magnet", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elon_Musk"}
{"title_page": "Abd al-Wahid ibn Sulayman", "text_new": "'''Abd al-Wahid ibn Sulayman ibn Abd al-Malik''' ({{lang-ar|\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0627\u062d\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0633\u0644\u064a\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0643|\u02bfAbd al-W\u0101\u1e25id ibn Sulaym\u0101n ibn \u02bfAbd al-Malik}}; {{floruit|720|750}}) was an [[Umayyad dynasty|Umayyad]] prince and the [[list of caliphal governors of Medina|governor]] of [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]] in 747\u2013748 during the reign of Caliph [[Marwan II]] ({{reign|744|750}}). He fled the post in 747/48 after failing to prevent the takeover of the two Islamic holy cities by the [[Kharijites]] during the [[Ibadi revolt]]. He was later executed by the [[Abbasids]] after their toppling of the [[Umayyad Caliphate]].\n\n==Early life==\nAbd al-Wahid was a son of Caliph [[Sulayman ibn Abd al-Malik|Sulayman]] ({{reign|715|717}}) and a grandson of Caliph [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|Abd al-Malik]] ({{reign|685|705}}).{{sfn|Williams|1985|p=90, note 252}} According to a contemporary poem preserved in the 10th-century ''[[Kitab al-aghani]]'' (Book of Songs), Abd al-Wahid rewarded the [[Taghlib]]ite poet al-Qutami (d. 747) with fifty camels loaded with wheat, dates and clothing for a [[panegyric]] praising the prince during the rule of Caliph [[Umar II]] ({{reign|717|720}}); Abd al-Wahid made the gift to al-Qutami shortly after hearing that Umar had refused to gift him the thirty camels al-Qutami had requested due to the caliph's apparent disdain for poetry.{{sfn|Bakhouch|2008\u20132009|pp=184\u2013185, note 80}}\n\n==Governorship of Medina==\n{{See also|Ibadi revolt}}\nIn 747 Abd al-Wahid was appointed the governor of [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]] by Caliph [[Marwan II]] ({{reign|744|750}}), his distant cousin.{{sfn|Williams|1985|p=90}} During the [[Hajj]] (annual Muslim pilgrimage to Mecca) in August 747, [[Kharijite]] rebels led by [[Abu Hamza al-Azdi]] entered Mecca and Abd al-Wahid entered a truce with them stipulating that each side could resume the Hajj in peace.{{sfn|Williams|1985|p=90}} As the two sides approached [[Mina]], a closing stage of the Hajj, the Kharijites \"pushed aside\" Abd al-Wahid and the pilgrims he led, according to [[al-Tabari]], leading the pilgrims to criticize the governor for not taking firmer action against Abu Hamza.{{sfn|Williams|1985|p=91}} Afterward, the latter encamped outside Mecca while Abd al-Wahid returned to the governor's palace in Mecca.{{sfn|Williams|1985|p=91}} Abd al-Wahid sent a delegation of Medinese nobles to persuade Abu Hamza to withdraw from the region, but Abu Hamza refused and Abd al-Wahid consequently abandoned Mecca to the Kharijites, who entered without a fight.{{sfn|Williams|1985|p=91}}\n\nUpon returning to Medina, Abd al-Wahid mobilized an army of local volunteers and appointed to its command his distant kinsman, Abd al-Aziz ibn Abd Allah ibn Amr, a great-grandson of Caliph [[Uthman]] ({{reign|644|656}}).{{sfn|Williams|1985|p=93}} On their way to Mecca, the Medinese volunteers, who lacked military experience, were ambushed by the Kharijites at the village of Qudayd between Medina and Mecca and Abd al-Aziz was slain.{{sfn|Williams|1985|pp=112\u2013114}} The Kharijites subsequently entered Medina in late 747 or early 748, spurring Abd al-Wahid to flee for [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]], the center of the Umayyad Caliphate. {{sfn|Williams|1985|p=113}}\n\n==Death and descendants==\nIn the aftermath of the toppling of the Umayyads and invasion of Syria by the [[Abbasids]] in 750, Abd al-Wahid went into hiding among friendly Arab tribes until being pardoned and promised safety by the Abbasid authorities.{{sfn|James|2012|p=73}} Later that year, however, he was executed with numerous other Umayyads by the [[Abbasids]] in [[Jund Filastin]] (military district of [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]]) at a banquet at an estate along [[Rosh HaAyin|Nahr Abi Futrus]] (Antipatris river),{{sfn|James|2012|p=74}} in the village of [[Qalansawa]],{{sfn|Robinson|2010|p=240}} or in the court of the Abbasid caliph [[al-Saffah]] ({{reign|750|754}}).{{sfn|Elad|2000|p=288, note 233}} According to the last account, Abd al-Wahid was singled out and seated next to the Abbasid caliph in honor of certain favors Abd al-Wahid had once granted the Abbasid family; after the caliph ordered his guards to execute the other Umayyads brought to his court by bashing in their skulls with maces, he reportedly told Abd al-Wahid \"there is no point in you staying alive after your people and your power have gone\", but granted him the dignity of death by the sword.{{sfn|James|2012|p=74}} \n\nA number of Umayyads fled the massacres of their family in Syria, Iraq, Egypt and Arabia and found refuge in [[al-Andalus]] (the [[Iberian Peninsula]]) where [[Abd al-Rahman I]], a son of Abd al-Wahid's cousin [[Mu'awiya ibn Hisham]], established the [[C\u00f3rdoba, Spain|Cordoba]]-based [[Umayyad emirate]] in 756. The sources record a number of descendants of Abd al-Wahid's sons Abd al-Malik and Abd al-Salam playing active roles in the emirate,{{sfn|Uzquiza Bartolom\u00e9|1994|p=459}} including a sixth-generation descendant of the former, Abd al-Malik ibn Muhammad al-Sulaymani (d. 970).{{sfn|Avila|1985|p=103}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |last1=Avila |first1=Maria Luisa |title=La sociedad hispanomusulmana al final del califato: aproximaci\u00f3n a un estudio demogr\u00e1fico |date=1985 |publisher=Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cient\u00edficas |location=Madrid |isbn=84-00-06045-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TFKdQVkltF0C&pg=PA103&lpg=PA103 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Bakhouch |first1=Mohamed |title=Le calife 'Umar b. 'Abd al-'Az\u012bz et les po\u00e8tes |journal=Bulletin d'\u00e9tudes orientales |date=2008\u20132009 |volume=58 |pages=161\u2013204 |url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/41608619 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Elad |first1=Amikam |title=The Ethnic Composition of the 'Abbasid Revolution: A Reevaluation of Some Recent Research |journal=Jerusalem Studies in Arabic and Islam |date=2000 |volume=24 |pages=246\u2013326 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=James |first1=David |title=A History of Early Al-Andalus: The Akhbar Majmu'a |date=2012 |publisher=Routledge |location=London and New York |isbn=978-0-415-66943-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YSipAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA183&lpg=PA73 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Robinson |first1=Chase F. |editor1-last=Suleiman |editor1-first=Yasir |title=Living Islamic History: Studies in Honour of Professor Carole Hillenbrand: Studies in Honour of Professor Carole Hillenbrand |date=2010 |publisher=Edinburgh University Press |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0-7486-3738-6 |pages=226-251 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QRirBgAAQBAJ |ref=harv |chapter=The Violence of the Abbasid Revolution}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Uzquiza Bartolom\u00e9 |first1=Ar\u00e1nzazu |editor1-last=Mar\u00edn |editor1-first=Manuela |title=Estudios onom\u00e1stico-biogr\u00e1ficos de Al-Andalus: V |date=1994 |publisher=Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cient\u00edficas |location=Madrid |isbn=84-00-07415-7 |pages=445\u2013462 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sTvD7V9qbUIC&pg=PA446 |ref=harv |chapter=Otros Linajes Omeyas en al-Andalus |language=Spanish}}\n*{{The History of al-Tabari |volume=27 |url={{Google Books|zTXwgEb6mcMC|plainurl=y}}}}\n\n[[Category:750 deaths]]\n[[Category:8th-century Arabs]]\n[[Category:8th-century executions by the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Umayyad dynasty]]\n[[Category:Umayyad governors of Medina]]\n", "text_old": "'''Abd al-Wahid ibn Sulayman ibn Abd al-Malik''' ({{lang-ar|\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0627\u062d\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0633\u0644\u064a\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0628\u0646 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u0643|\u02bfAbd al-W\u0101\u1e25id ibn Sulaym\u0101n ibn \u02bfAbd al-Malik}}; {{floruit|720|750}}) was an [[Umayyad dynasty|Umayyad]] prince and the [[list of caliphal governors of Medina|governor]] of [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]] in 747\u2013748 during the reign of Caliph [[Marwan II]] ({{reign|744|750}}). He fled the post in 747/48 after failing to prevent the takeover of the two Islamic holy cities by the [[Kharijites]] during the [[Ibadi revolt]]. He was later executed by the [[Abbasids]] after their toppling of the [[Umayyad Caliphate]].\n\n==Early life==\nAbd al-Wahid was a son of Caliph [[Sulayman ibn Abd al-Malik|Sulayman]] ({{reign|715|717}}) and a grandson of Caliph [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan|Abd al-Malik]] ({{reign|685|705}}).{{sfn|Williams|1985|p=90, note 252}} According to a contemporary poem preserved in the 10th-century ''[[Kitab al-aghani]]'' (Book of Songs), Abd al-Wahid rewarded the [[Taghlib]]ite poet al-Qutami (d. 747) with fifty camels loaded with wheat, dates and clothing for a [[panegyric]] praising the prince during the rule of Caliph [[Umar II]] ({{reign|717|720}}); Abd al-Wahid made the gift to al-Qutami shortly after hearing that Umar had refused to gift him the thirty camels al-Qutami had requested due to the caliph's apparent disdain for poetry.{{sfn|Bakhouch|2008\u20132009|pp=184\u2013185, note 80}}\n\n==Governorship of Medina==\n{{See also|Ibadi revolt}}\nIn 747 Abd al-Wahid was appointed the governor of [[Mecca]] and [[Medina]] by Caliph [[Marwan II]] ({{reign|744|750}}), his distant cousin.{{sfn|Williams|1985|p=90}} During the [[Hajj]] (annual Muslim pilgrimage to Mecca) in August 747, [[Kharijite]] rebels led by [[Abu Hamza al-Azdi]] entered Mecca and Abd al-Wahid entered a truce with them stipulating that each side could resume the Hajj in peace.{{sfn|Williams|1985|p=90}} As the two sides approached [[Mina]], a closing stage of the Hajj, the Kharijites \"pushed aside\" Abd al-Wahid and the pilgrims he led, according to [[al-Tabari]], leading the pilgrims to criticize the governor for not taking firmer action against Abu Hamza.{{sfn|Williams|1985|p=91}} Afterward, the latter encamped outside Mecca while Abd al-Wahid returned to the governor's palace in Mecca.{{sfn|Williams|1985|p=91}} Abd al-Wahid sent a delegation of Medinese nobles to persuade Abu Hamza to withdraw from the region, but Abu Hamza refused and Abd al-Wahid consequently abandoned Mecca to the Kharijites, who entered without a fight.{{sfn|Williams|1985|p=91}}\n\nUpon returning to Medina, Abd al-Wahid mobilized an army of local volunteers and appointed to its command his distant kinsman, Abd al-Aziz ibn Abd Allah ibn Amr, a great-grandson of Caliph [[Uthman]] ({{reign|644|656}}).{{sfn|Williams|1985|p=93}} On their way to Mecca, the Medinese volunteers, who lacked military experience, were ambushed by the Kharijites at the village of Qudayd between Medina and Mecca and Abd al-Aziz was slain.{{sfn|Williams|1985|pp=112\u2013114}} The Kharijites subsequently entered Medina in late 747 or early 748, spurring Abd al-Wahid to flee for [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria]], the center of the Umayyad Caliphate. {{sfn|Williams|1985|p=113}}\n\n==Death and descendants==\nIn the aftermath of the toppling of the Umayyads and invasion of Syria by the [[Abbasids]] in 750, Abd al-Wahid went into hiding among friendly Arab tribes until being pardoned and promised safety by the Abbasid authorities.{{sfn|James|2012|p=73}} Later that year, however, he was executed with numerous other Umayyads by the [[Abbasids]] in [[Jund Filastin]] (military district of [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]]) at a banquet at an estate along [[Rosh HaAyin|Nahr Abi Futrus]] (Antipatris river),{{sfn|James|2012|p=74}} in the village of [[Qalansawa]],{{sfn|Robinson|2010|p=240}} or in the court of the Abbasid caliph [[al-Saffah]] ({{reign|750|754}}).{{sfn|Elad|2000|p=288, note 233}} According to the last account, Abd al-Wahid was singled out and seated next to the Abbasid caliph in honor of certain favors Abd al-Wahid had once granted the Abbasid family; after the caliph ordered his guards to execute the other Umayyads brought to his court by bashing in their skulls with maces, he reportedly told Abd al-Wahid \"there is no point in you staying alive after your people and your power have gone\", but granted him the dignity of death by the sword.{{sfn|James|2012|p=74}} \n\nA number of Umayyads fled the massacres of their family in Syria, Iraq, Egypt and Arabia and found refuge in [[al-Andalus]] (the [[Iberian Peninsula]]) where [[Abd al-Rahman I]], a son of Abd al-Wahid's cousin [[Mu'awiya ibn Hisham]], established the [[Cordoba]]-based [[Umayyad emirate]] in 756. The sources record a number of descendants of Abd al-Wahid's sons Abd al-Malik and Abd al-Salam playing active roles in the emirate,{{sfn|Uzquiza Bartolom\u00e9|1994|p=459}} including a sixth-generation descendant of the former, Abd al-Malik ibn Muhammad al-Sulaymani (d. 970).{{sfn|Avila|1985|p=103}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book |last1=Avila |first1=Maria Luisa |title=La sociedad hispanomusulmana al final del califato: aproximaci\u00f3n a un estudio demogr\u00e1fico |date=1985 |publisher=Consejo Superior de Investigaciones Cient\u00edficas |location=Madrid |isbn=84-00-06045-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TFKdQVkltF0C&pg=PA103&lpg=PA103 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Bakhouch |first1=Mohamed |title=Le calife 'Umar b. 'Abd al-'Az\u012bz et les po\u00e8tes |journal=Bulletin d'\u00e9tudes orientales |date=2008\u20132009 |volume=58 |pages=161\u2013204 |url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/41608619 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Elad |first1=Amikam |title=The Ethnic Composition of the 'Abbasid Revolution: A Reevaluation of Some Recent Research |journal=Jerusalem Studies in Arabic and Islam |date=2000 |volume=24 |pages=246\u2013326 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=James |first1=David |title=A History of Early Al-Andalus: The Akhbar Majmu'a |date=2012 |publisher=Routledge |location=London and New York |isbn=978-0-415-66943-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YSipAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA